Review.Summary: A New World of Music: Drum and Bass
Review.Content:
I like all kinds of music: classical, romantic, contemporary, reggae, world, rock (in all its forms: sixties innovative, seventies and eighties' departure into more electric, and the nineties' and 2000's progressive forms), jazz, blues, country (only some of it from the Stones or Blind Melon), rap and hip hop, and electronic in its different forms (fusion, ambient, progressive house, trance, and garage). However, I have an affinity for drum and bass. I don't know why... it started with New Forms in 97. Through the last 8 years it has remained there although sometimes I lost touch with it.

This affinity is extremely strong however. I'm sure it's about taste and varies from human to human, but there is something special about this sound that is too difficult to put into words.

Nu Tone has created something special for the world. This is an essential album for anyone that likes music. Just plain music as an artistically representation of sound from somewhere in the human consciousness.

Brave Nu World picks up where some other drum and bass artists left. It continues the tradition started in 1997 (Reprazent's New Forms), 2000 (Reprazent's In the Mode), 2003 (London Elektricity's Billion Dollar Gravy) and 2004 (Tali's Lyric on my Lip). It shows that drum and bass is always advancing. Anything can be done. Like its predecessors this is an honest, beautiful, and essential work of art. I strongly recommend it. Like any drum and basic classics mentioned above, this album need to be in your collection.

-AdV

Let me start this by saying that I was trully blown away by this album. Everything in here flows so well, it's almost out of this world. Right from the start with smooth and ear pleasing "seven years" to the last song on this album, everything sounds so good. I have been trying to follow Hospital's DJs and all of them have a great talent, but Nu:tone just raised the bar on this one.

Some of my favorites are:
"seven years", Natalie Williams sounds awesome on this one.
"can we?", as far as I am concerned anything with London Electricity is garanteed to be good, and this one was.
"three bags full" I can't stop listening to that one.
"New boy" There is something great when you mix jazz and D'n'B.
"strange encounter" another one with Natalie Williams, this is one great.
"Breathless" Great song.

Brave Nu World is the outstanding long-play debut from London's own Dan Gresham AKA Nu:Tone. This album delivers a fresh milestone on the ever-evolving D&B scene. From the beginning to the end this is a Merry-Go-Round Utopia that picks up from where the last song left. Add this a dancefloor flavor and you'll get the idea! There is no remixes here; It's all original songs!

Nu:Tone makes a clear statement with his original style. Every song stands on it own. You will feel a fresh burst of tunes and riffs that will last you even in your sleep. From the sultry beats of "Seven Years" (backed up by the sexy vocals of Natalie Williams), the club stomping "Right Now", the nursery-fresh beats from "EBB+Flow" (this one will get you inner child up and romping); even the resurgence of all-time favorite Soul 2 Soul's Rose Windross vocals in "All Over the World" makes us feel like it's OK to be groovy!

Mr. Gresham let us know that he's very influenced by his goodie crew that includes Logistics, High-Contrast, Calibre, XRS, Patife, etc., but at the same time, blast us with so much freshness and originality to let us know that he on his own is a force to be reckoned with.

Nu:Tone clearly got what it takes to be on the top pillar with the D&B big dogs!

EditorialReview.Content: A heartfelt collection of Neo-Traditional Country songs with roots firmly planted in the fertile soil of yesteryear while keeping a shining face turned upward to the bright sunshine of today. Clever, romantic, you'll laugh 'til it hurts 'cuz you know the songs are so painfully true (at least for somebody). If you like old country music, you'll love the Nu-Tone Wranglers - If you don't like country music, this is the record to change your mind. Just buy it , Okay? We need the money and someone you either love or hate will be sure to go crazy for this treasure-trove of tunesmithing."
